{"type":"message","id":"26f8f1ad","parentId":"17db2879","timestamp":"2026-04-28T10:44:35.825Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_xd2embchy8zt_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:**Channel:** Alex Finn  \n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:Alex Finn reviews ChatGPT 5.5 combined with the Codex desktop app and compares it head-to-head with Opus 4.7 and Claude Code.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:| **Limits** | ✅ Way higher, resets frequently | ❌ Getting lower |\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:| **Integrations (Linear, etc.)** | ✅ Deep integrations | ❌ Limited |\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:**Verdict:** ChatGPT 5.5 + Codex wins for coding. Alex switched his workflow permanently — higher limits, smarter model, better integrations, computer use. The one remaining Claude strengths: better default UIs, slightly better personality.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:**Note:** Alex mentions doing a separate follow-up on OpenClaw — whether to use Claude or ChatGPT with OpenClaw specifically.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:I've been using Chat GPT 5.5 non-stop since it released a few days ago and I'm blown away. I figured out a workflow that I'm going to show you in this video that I don't think I've seen anywhere else that will completely change how you build with AI. I also put it head-to-head with Opus 47 and Claude code in hundreds of tests and I can confidently tell you one of these two are better than the other. In this video, I'll go over what makes Chat GPT 5.5 so different, why the Codex app is a complete game-changer, show you my master workflow for both beginners and advanced, then tell you what you should be using once and for all, Opus 47 and Claude code or Chat GPT 5.5 and Codex. This is going to be a banger. Let's lock in and get into it. This isn't a channel where we spend 20 minutes reading blog posts, looking at charts, and looking at fake benchmark tests. No, we're not doing that. We get straight into the action. So, this is Codex. This is the desktop Codex app. This is by far the best way to be using Chat GPT 5.5. I basically spend 90% of my day now inside of this app. So, what you need to do immediately is go and download this. They have released so many updates over the last few days to this. It is basically a completely different app. So, if you haven't downloaded and used Codex for desktop yet, go ahead, pause this video, do it now. So, everything we do, you can do it with me together. So, real quick, we'll talk about the big improvements I've experienced in Chat GPT 5.5. Number one, and this is the biggest improvement in my eyes, takes action by default. Chat GPT 5.4, the biggest issue is I tell it to do something, it doesn't actually do it. I have to sit there and beg on my knees, \"Please, Chat GPT 5.4, do what I tell you to do.\" And it wouldn't do it. It was very smart, but not about that action. 5.5, slightly less chatty. I felt like I was reading a novel every time I would give 5.4 a prompt. I literally would crash out sometimes and say, \"Please, for the love of God, just stop saying so much. Get straight to the point.\" That is not as much of an issue with 5.5. Still a little bit of an issue, not as much of an issue. Better personality. 5.4 was a cold Terminator machine. It did not feel warm to talk to. It was not quite as fun to talk to. 5.5, better personality. Not perfect personality, better personality. And a big one here, it is significantly smarter. It creates excellent, excellent, excellent code. I basically, over the last few days of testing this, have gotten zero bugs out of the code it's written. Zero, zero, zero. So, it is much, much, much smarter, which is amazing to see. Now, these are all big, great improvements, but I'll tell you what, the biggest improvement comes from the experience of using it inside this app I'm showing you here. This is the new Codex desktop app. You need to do yourself a favor. You need to pause this video immediately. You need to go download this. Go download the Codex desktop app because this is incredible. This is where I've spent 95% of my waking moments over the last few days is inside this app. There are 20,000 different features that make it amazing that I'll be going through in this video, but you need to be downloading this immediately. 5.5 with this Codex app is a match made in heaven. It's a beautiful harmony of AI genius. So, here's the plan for the video and here's why you need to buckle in immediately. I'm going to build out a basic app using this Codex app. I'm going to show you how to use it, many the incredible features. Once we got a good feel for the app, we're comfortable with it, we know what it's doing, then we'll go to a super advanced workflow that I promise will change your life. It has changed everything for me. It's helped me build apps literally, I'm not even joking, 10 times better and faster. We'll go into that advanced workflow right after we get comfortable with this and I go through the strengths of the model and the app. When we talk about Chat GPT 5.5, we're also implicitly talking about this app as well just because they work so well together. So, getting off a few things, let's just do quick tour of the app. We'll spend a couple seconds here. Over on the left-hand side, everything is organized by project. You'll see a lot of new project 1 2 3 4 5 over here. That's cuz I've been doing insane amounts of tests over the last few days. But, what's great is is you can multitask so easily in here. You can start off multiple chats in a project, work on the back end while you're working on the front end, while you have a chat going where you're game planning the entire app itself. This is a beautiful part about the Codex app. Then down below, what's amazing is you can also have chats. So, they've combined into this super app not only the coding section, but also you have a chat section. For those who build things, you need to be having chats separate from your building, separate from your coding. So, as one goes at it, as you're coding and building something, you can have a chat going where you're doing high-level planning, design, development, whatever it is, you can have those separate chats going. So, you can strategize and brainstorm on the app and business you're building. So, it's beautiful they combined this all in one. In the Claude app, it's very different. Everything is separated out. So, you have your chats and then you have to go over here and you switch to your code. And to talk to one or the other, you're switching between these entirely different interfaces. You can see even the colors of the background are different. It's just completely different app. I don't like that separation quite as much. With Codex, it is all tightly integrated, which is beautiful. One thing you also want to do before you start building is go into settings down here. Go into your settings. Go over to computer use and make sure this is turned on. For me, it was off by default. Make sure you turn this on. This is one of the new amazing features that they just dropped in here where it can control your entire computer. It's clear they're trying to eat open claw and put it into this Codex app. I'm fine with it. You just got to make sure you turn on this computer use right here, which will allow Codex to do a lot of really cool things, including testing your apps, doing different things on your computer. It's all part of the super app they're going for. So, let's do this. Let's build out an app. And as we build out the app, I'll take you around, show you the different features, show you all the cool things going on so you can see what makes this model so powerful and what makes this app so beautiful. So, make sure you go up here, you create a new project, put it in a new folder. What we're going to be building today is a prompt library app. It's an app where you can take your best prompts, the ones you reuse all often, and save it. This is great because after you're done building this with me, you can use it for whatever you want. But, let's do this. One thing you need to know, there's a lot going on here. We've tested it all. I've tested low, medium, high, extra high for intelligence. I know it's very tempting to do extra high for everything. When you're using Claude code, you use the highest level for everything cuz you just get the best results. But, that's different here. They made Chat GPT 5.5, and this is one of the reasons why it's a really good model, very intelligent, very efficient with its intelligence. So, you actually don't need to be using extra high for everything. That can actually be a hindrance in many scenarios. So, what you want to do is you actually want to use medium for everything. I tested it all. Medium is the sweet spot. You pretty much want to use medium for everything. So, now that we're there, also full access. Instead of default permissions, they have to click accept, accept, accept, accept all the time. Just go straight into full access. We've gone past the point of AI doing dangerous things on your computer. You can do full access. It'll make your workflow so much faster. So, let's start building this out and we're going to start off right off the rip with what is one of the most amazing, beautiful strengths of Codex and 5.5 that dominates Claude code, and that is the integration with the image to model. For those who don't know, if you've been living under a rock the last week, OpenAI released the image to model and it is by far and away, not even close, the best image generation model on planet Earth. It destroys Nano Banana. thing here is it is completely built into Codex. So, let me show you how I do this. Let's get into this workflow and show you some cool things you can do. All right, so here we go. Take this prompt. I'll put it down below. What you're going to see here is how I use the built-in image gen model to first come up with an interface. This is going to allow us to make much better, more beautiful interfaces. This is again one of the strengths of Chat GPT 5.5 with Codex. deeply integrated with that incredible new image gen model. I want to build a prompt library app. By the way, if you do this with me, you'll have an amazing app you can use whenever you want. It'll allow you to go and revisit all your most commonly used prompts. So, build this with me here. The user should be able to save commonly used prompts, to see their library, and older prompts saved. They should be able to favorite and organize them. Let's make this a beautiful but simple interface like linear. Please use the image gen model to first generate four or five options for this interface. This is something Claude code doesn't have. They don't have an image gen model at all. Not only does Chat GPT have the greatest image gen model in the world, but it is deeply integrated into Codex. So, let's do this. Also, by the way, you can turn up the speed to fast. Their fast model is incredible. And their usage they give you is so high that you really can get away with using it a ton. So, I'm going to hit send on this. And the first thing it's going to do is get us some interfaces we can look at and choose first. All right, looks like it finished. And look at this, five different interfaces for us to choose from. This is something Claude code cannot do because it doesn't have any sort of image gen in it. Let's take a quick look and choose one. Again, this is something you should be doing with basically every app you're building is taking advantage of this incredible image gen model to first figure out what you want your interface to look like. Okay, so we got our first one. Looking nice, a little busy. I think it's a little busy. Let's check out the second one. I like that a little bit better. Let's see the third one. Ooh, I like the card style. I think I'm going to go with the card style. Let's just check out four and five here. Four, okay. Okay, looking nice. And then five. I think this is the winner. Green's my favorite color. Let's go. Let's do this. I'm just going to copy this. I'm going to put it in. I'm going to paste it here. I'm going to do this. I'm going to say, \"I love the fifth one, the one with the green accents and cards. Can we start building the app based on that?\" And I know, I know, there's a click to dictate button. Everyone in every video says, \"Hey, why don't you just dictate?\" I like typing. I'm a typer. I enjoy typing. So, we're going to do this. We have it full access. I just do full access for everything. I fully trust the model. We're going to keep it on medium, have the speed high, and I'm going to hit send, and it is going to get to work here. What we're going to see as it builds this out is some of the amazing functionality that really separates ChatGPT from any of the other apps or tools out there. I can't wait to show you what happens when we get into the testing part when it comes to computer use and different things it does with the built-in browser. Stick around for this. I think you're going to be blown away by what it can do. Also, as it builds, we're going to get into a much more advanced workflow after we go through this. I just want to show you all the kind of bells and whistles of ChatGPT 5.5 with Codex. Then we'll get into super advanced right after. I feel like this is a little bit more fun than reading through blog posts, right? I feel like this is a cooler way to do this. And then also, right after that is the big comparison with this in Claude Code with the final recommendation. So, stick around for that. By the way, if you learned anything at all so far, make sure to leave a like down below. Subscribe, turn notifications. Coming up in the next week, I'll do a live boot camp of Codex inside the Vibe Coding Academy. The link for that is down below. It's the number one AI community on planet Earth, so check that out as well. All right, looks like it finished going. Now, here is some really cool strength of the Codex app with ChatGPT 5.5. The integrations with so many different tools are incredible. So, first of all, built-in browser. So, you pop it open and you can immediately see it works with this built-in browser. And if I even go into full screen mode, you can see a lot more of it. And it basically looks exactly like the image gen we got as we were planning this, which is amazing. But let's look at some of the built-in tools here that there's basically no other app on planet Earth has. We can now start editing this app straight from this live browser in Codex. So, there's many tools we have here. First of all, we have this annotate. So, if I go in here, as you can see as I hover around the app, it selects different elements and I can say for it to change different things. So, if I want to go in here, let's add a favorites button up here. So, as I'm building a new prompt, I can immediately put into favorites. So, I put it there and I can say, \"Let's add a favorites button.\" This is one of my favorite ways to use ChatGPT 5.5 in Codex is instead of just prompting back and forth, I just go straight into the app and I start annotating live on the app. It's like I'm actually building the app inside the app rather than just talking to a chatbot. So, I'm going to say this, I'm going to hit that, I'm going to add it, and then I'm going to hit send on that. And now it's going to get to work. This is one of the most fun ways for me to be building out my apps. And boom, just like that, there's your favorites but[... 49252 more characters truncated]"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":62,"aggregated":"/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:**Channel:** Alex Finn  \n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:Alex Finn reviews ChatGPT 5.5 combined with the Codex desktop app and compares it head-to-head with Opus 4.7 and Claude Code.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:| **Limits** | ✅ Way higher, resets frequently | ❌ Getting lower |\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:| **Integrations (Linear, etc.)** | ✅ Deep integrations | ❌ Limited |\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:**Verdict:** ChatGPT 5.5 + Codex wins for coding. Alex switched his workflow permanently — higher limits, smarter model, better integrations, computer use. The one remaining Claude strengths: better default UIs, slightly better personality.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:**Note:** Alex mentions doing a separate follow-up on OpenClaw — whether to use Claude or ChatGPT with OpenClaw specifically.\n/Users/bobbygalletta/Desktop/SecondBrain/Research/alex-finn/2026-04-27/2026-04-27 - ChatGPT 5.5 Codex - Alex Finn.md:I've been using Chat GPT 5.5 non-stop since it released a few days ago and I'm blown away. I figured out a workflow that I'm going to show you in this video that I don't think I've seen anywhere else tha