{"type":"message","id":"08fec13d","parentId":"d5a0a01d","timestamp":"2026-04-28T14:36:35.726Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_f2205giesfzr_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Transcript:\nClaudebot is the most powerful AI tool\nin the world. The issue is if you use it\nthe wrong way, it could cost you\nthousands of dollars a month and you\nwouldn't even know it. In this video,\nI'll show you how you can run your 24/7\nautonomous AI employee for a fraction\nthe cost while still getting the same\npower out of it. I'll go through every\nsingle spending level and show you how\nto set up Claude to match your exact\nbudget. By the end of this video, if you\nstick with me to the end, you'll have\nyour Claudebot running even more\npowerfully for way less money. I'm about\nto save you tons of cash. Let's get into\nit. So, I'm going to go through every\nsingle major use case you can do with\nClaudebot and then go through what is\nthe best model and tool you should be\nusing for each use case and show you the\none you should be using if you're trying\nto save money. Claudebot is amazing\nbecause you can plug in a different AI\nmodel or tool for every single little\nthing it does. So, by watching this\nvideo, you'll not only know what the\nbest models are, what the cheapest\nmodels are, but you also learn about\nsome new use cases I bet you haven't\neven thought of. So, you're not only\ngoing to be using CloudBot better, but\nyou'll be saving tons of money. A double\nwhammy all for the cost of a like down\nbelow. So, let's get right into it.\nFirst use case I want to cover with\nClaudebot is the brain. The way I like\nto think about Claudebot is the brain is\nwhat you communicate with, what you're\nchatting back and forth with, and then\nthe muscles are every use case the brain\ncalls on. You want to make sure you have\nthe best model for the brain and then\nthe best model for each muscle it calls.\nThe brain is what you're talking with\nwhen you're inside Clawbot. It is very\ncritical when you choose a brain model,\nyou choose one that's not only\nintelligent, so it knows which muscles\nto call, but also is warm and\npersonable. When you're talking to your\nclawbot, you want it to feel human.\nThat's where like half the fun comes\nfrom is just feeling like you're talking\nto a human being. The best model if\nmoney is not a thing in your entire life\nis Opus 45. It is the most intelligent\nAI model in the world and is also the\nmost warm and personable model in the\nworld. It is the best to talk to. The\nissue is that's extremely expensive. So,\nlet's talk about the cheapest one you\nwant to use and that is Kimmy K2.5. This\nis an extremely cheap model. In fact,\nthey have a bunch of specials at all\ntimes. So, you can get like a month\nbasically for free. This is near opus\nlevel intelligence and near opus level\npersonality for an absolute fraction of\nthe cost. If you are concerned about\ncost savings, this is one of the single\nbiggest levers you can pull to save\nmoney. The performance will still be\nreally good from your brain. The\npersonality will still be decently warm.\nThat's probably the biggest weakness of\ndowngrading from Opus is like Opus just\nfeels human being. But you will be\nspending so much less money from a pure\nchatbot perspective. You know, just\nchatting with your Clawbot. If you don't\nwant to spend thousands of dollars a\nmonth on Opus, Kimmy K2.5 is the place\nto go. Now, here's one that people don't\nthink about that actually Sneaky costs\nyou a ton of money, and that is the\nheartbeat. For those that don't know,\nevery 10 minutes there is a heartbeat\ninside your Clawbot. And basically what\nthis heartbeat does is check to see if\nthere's any tasks your Claudebot needs\nto do. Here's the issue. It by default\nuses whatever your brain model is. So if\nyou're like most people watching this\nvideo and you're using Opus 45 for your\nbrain model, it's calling Opus 4